WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.000
Welcome to the final chapter of this case study.

2
00:00:04.000 --> 00:00:07.960
We are finally ready to incorporate the make side of the decision.

3
00:00:07.960 --> 00:00:07.960


4
00:00:07.960 --> 00:00:07.960


5
00:00:07.960 --> 00:00:10.560
Just like with the buy option, it is important to

6
00:00:10.560 --> 00:00:13.880
calculate the full cost of production when considering the make option.

7
00:00:13.880 --> 00:00:14.800


8
00:00:14.800 --> 00:00:14.800


9
00:00:14.800 --> 00:00:18.400
In the Buy option, our data were quotes from suppliers.

10
00:00:18.400 --> 00:00:18.400


11
00:00:18.400 --> 00:00:18.400


12
00:00:18.400 --> 00:00:21.880
In the Make option, we will use internal estimates.

13
00:00:21.880 --> 00:00:21.920


14
00:00:21.920 --> 00:00:21.920


15
00:00:21.920 --> 00:00:25.120
Internal estimates are similar to quotes because they have the

16
00:00:25.120 --> 00:00:29.920
expected unit cost and enough information to calculate upfront investments.

17
00:00:29.920 --> 00:00:30.880


18
00:00:30.880 --> 00:00:30.920


19
00:00:30.920 --> 00:00:36.840
Unlike quotes from external suppliers, internal estimates are not binding offers.

20
00:00:36.840 --> 00:00:41.760
If the cost of production changes, your company still has to absorb those costs.

21
00:00:41.760 --> 00:00:41.760


22
00:00:41.760 --> 00:00:41.760


23
00:00:41.760 --> 00:00:49.320
Internal Estimates include unit costs - which are comprised of raw materials, energy costs, and labor costs.

24
00:00:49.320 --> 00:00:53.800
These are costs that increase for every additional unit we produce.

25
00:00:53.800 --> 00:00:53.800


26
00:00:53.800 --> 00:00:53.840


27
00:00:53.840 --> 00:00:59.040
Internal Estimates also include data about the equipment used to manufacture the parts.

28
00:00:59.040 --> 00:01:02.160
Depending on our existing machine capacity and production

29
00:01:02.160 --> 00:01:07.520
demand, we may or may not need to invest in new manufacturing equipment.

30
00:01:07.520 --> 00:01:07.520


31
00:01:07.520 --> 00:01:07.520


32
00:01:07.520 --> 00:01:12.160
The internal estimates include the equipment model number, the manufacturing capacity of

33
00:01:12.160 --> 00:01:18.800
each machine, the existing available capacity, and the cost of an additional piece of equipment.

34
00:01:18.800 --> 00:01:18.800


35
00:01:18.800 --> 00:01:18.800


36
00:01:18.800 --> 00:01:22.760
Note that the capacity for each machine is different for each part.

37
00:01:22.760 --> 00:01:22.760


38
00:01:22.760 --> 00:01:22.760


39
00:01:22.760 --> 00:01:26.400
If production demand exceeds existing capacity, we need to

40
00:01:26.400 --> 00:01:30.160
include the cost of new equipment in the full cost for the Make option.

41
00:01:30.160 --> 00:01:30.160


42
00:01:30.160 --> 00:01:30.920


43
00:01:30.920 --> 00:01:36.360
For the Make versus Buy decision, we should only consider the incremental costs of our decision.

44
00:01:36.360 --> 00:01:44.960
Incremental costs are new costs introduced by our make-or-buy decision, not sunk costs that exist before the decision.

45
00:01:44.960 --> 00:01:44.960


46
00:01:44.960 --> 00:01:44.960


47
00:01:44.960 --> 00:01:49.000
If we already have a piece of manufacturing equipment, its cost

48
00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:52.400
should not be considered incremental to the Make versus Buy decision.

49
00:01:52.400 --> 00:01:52.400


50
00:01:52.400 --> 00:01:52.400


51
00:01:52.400 --> 00:01:57.960
Like with most things in life, incremental costs are easier to understand with pizza.

52
00:01:57.960 --> 00:01:57.960


53
00:01:57.960 --> 00:01:57.960


54
00:01:57.960 --> 00:02:03.200
Let’s return to the question of whether to buy pizza or make it on your own.

55
00:02:03.200 --> 00:02:03.200


56
00:02:03.200 --> 00:02:03.200


57
00:02:03.200 --> 00:02:05.280
Let’s assume you already own one oven.

58
00:02:05.280 --> 00:02:05.280


59
00:02:05.280 --> 00:02:05.280


60
00:02:05.280 --> 00:02:09.760
To make one pizza, you need to buy dough, cheese, and sauce.

61
00:02:09.760 --> 00:02:13.160
These costs should be included in your full cost.

62
00:02:13.160 --> 00:02:17.800
You already have an oven, so that is a sunk cost and should not be included.

63
00:02:17.800 --> 00:02:17.800


64
00:02:17.800 --> 00:02:17.800


65
00:02:17.800 --> 00:02:23.080
Now let’s imagine you want to have a party serving ten pizzas for friends.

66
00:02:23.080 --> 00:02:26.760
Your full cost now includes ten pizzas worth of dough, cheese, and

67
00:02:26.760 --> 00:02:31.440
sauce, but your single oven might not be able to make ten pizzas quickly enough.

68
00:02:31.440 --> 00:02:31.440


69
00:02:31.440 --> 00:02:32.240


70
00:02:32.240 --> 00:02:35.840
You may also need to buy or rent another oven to meet the demand.

71
00:02:35.840 --> 00:02:42.360
The cost of this second oven is an incremental cost and should be included in the full cost of the Make option.

72
00:02:42.360 --> 00:02:42.360


73
00:02:42.360 --> 00:02:42.360


74
00:02:42.360 --> 00:02:47.560
You may need to hire someone to help make ten pizzas, or your friends can help out.

75
00:02:47.560 --> 00:02:47.560


76
00:02:47.560 --> 00:02:47.560


77
00:02:47.560 --> 00:02:52.240
While our incremental costs in this course focus on equipment investments,

78
00:02:52.240 --> 00:02:58.160
incremental costs can also include other costs such as facilities and hiring new salaried employees.

79
00:02:58.160 --> 00:02:58.160


80
00:02:58.160 --> 00:02:58.800


81
00:02:58.800 --> 00:03:02.200
If the current staff and facilities can handle the new production requirements,

82
00:03:02.200 --> 00:03:07.840
there is no need to include their cost in the full incremental cost for the make decision.

83
00:03:07.840 --> 00:03:07.840


84
00:03:07.840 --> 00:03:07.840


85
00:03:07.840 --> 00:03:11.880
The full cost for the make option is similar to the buy option.

86
00:03:11.880 --> 00:03:11.880


87
00:03:11.880 --> 00:03:16.800
The full cost is the extended cost plus any incremental investment cost.

88
00:03:16.800 --> 00:03:22.160
In this course, we can calculate our required investment cost by

89
00:03:22.160 --> 00:03:25.840
looking at our existing capacity versus the expected production volume.

90
00:03:25.840 --> 00:03:25.840


91
00:03:25.840 --> 00:03:25.840


92
00:03:25.840 --> 00:03:30.640
If the expected production volume exceeds the current capacity, we

93
00:03:30.640 --> 00:03:34.560
must include the incremental investment cost in our full cost calculation.

94
00:03:34.560 --> 00:03:34.560


95
00:03:34.560 --> 00:03:34.560


96
00:03:34.560 --> 00:03:38.360
To calculate the number of machines required to purchase, we

97
00:03:38.360 --> 00:03:46.240
subtract our existing capacity from our production volume, then divide the remaining volume by the equipment capacity of a new machine.

98
00:03:46.240 --> 00:03:46.240


99
00:03:46.240 --> 00:03:46.240


100
00:03:46.240 --> 00:03:53.040
Note that we have to round up to the nearest whole machine because we cannot purchase half of a piece of equipment.

101
00:03:53.040 --> 00:03:58.320
We can use the DAX ROUNDUP() function to round to the next whole number.

102
00:03:58.320 --> 00:03:58.320


103
00:03:58.320 --> 00:03:58.320


104
00:03:58.320 --> 00:04:06.400
Let's use this to calculate our make full cost and finish up our make versus buy tool!

